{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"060da279-e89b-4fd2-9b77-7c788984046e","content":"Here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using stdio transport:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place this file at **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root.\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means VS Code communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Make sure your server reads MCP JSON-RPC messages from stdin and writes responses to stdout (don't use `Console.WriteLine` for logging — use stderr instead).\n- If you've already published the server, replace `dotnet run --project ...` with the path to the built executable.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot Chat panel in agent mode (`@workspace`) and your server's tools should appear automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a1c049e9-3ede-459a-a444-c4fb17279ebe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist, but the user is asking how to configure it. I can still provide the configuration guidance.","outputTokens":287,"requestId":"F3C2:800AA:1E249D3:22706AD:69F54E1A"},"id":"001ae18a-5888-40cd-ad6b-9eb811c27588","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:06:42.025Z","parentId":"646e0c95-4dfb-4874-9489-3b45b661c03a"}
